Heredity: Heredity is the passing of traits (characters) from parents to offspring through genes.

**Basic terms you must know:
| Term                | Meaning                                                                                                 |
| ------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Trait**           | Any **characteristic** that can be inherited (e.g., eye color, height, etc.)                            |
| **Gene**            | A **unit of heredity** made of DNA that controls a specific trait                                       |
| **Allele**          | Different forms of a gene (e.g., Tall (T) and short (t) for height)                                     |
| **Genotype**        | Genetic makeup of an organism (e.g., TT, Tt, tt)                                                        |
| **Phenotype**       | Physical appearance (e.g., Tall or Short)                                                               |
| **Dominant Trait**  | The trait that is **expressed even in one copy** (e.g., T in Tt)                                        |
| **Recessive Trait** | The trait that is **masked by dominant one**, expressed only when both alleles are recessive (e.g., tt) |
| **Homozygous**      | Both alleles are same (TT or tt)                                                                        |
| **Heterozygous**    | Two different alleles (Tt)                                                                              |
| **Hybrid**          | Offspring obtained by crossing two parents with **different traits**                                    |
| **Pure line**       | Offspring obtained from parents with **same traits for many generations**                               |


**Mandels experiment: fathet of genetics:
üß† Who was Mendel?
Gregor Johann Mendel (1822‚Äì1884) was an Austrian monk and scientist.
He is known as the Father of Genetics.
He performed experiments on pea plants (Pisum sativum) for 7 years (1856‚Äì1863) in the garden of his monastery.

  **Why mandels choose pea plants:
| Reason                              | Explanation                               |
| ----------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| 1. Short life cycle                 | Many generations could be studied quickly |
| 2. Clear contrasting traits         | e.g. Tall/short, Round/wrinkled seeds     |
| 3. Self-pollinating                 | Natural self-pollination ensures purity   |
| 4. Can be cross-pollinated manually | Allowed control of breeding               |
| 5. Easy to cultivate                | Grows easily and produces many seeds      |

  **Traits studied by mandels:

| Character          | Dominant Trait | Recessive Trait |
| ------------------ | -------------- | --------------- |
| 1. Plant height    | Tall           | Dwarf           |
| 2. Flower color    | Violet         | White           |
| 3. Flower position | Axial          | Terminal        |
| 4. Pod color       | Green          | Yellow          |
| 5. Pod shape       | Inflated       | Constricted     |
| 6. Seed shape      | Round          | Wrinkled        |
| 7. Seed color      | Yellow         | Green           |

  üß¨ Mendel‚Äôs Experimental Steps
1Ô∏è‚É£ Monohybrid Cross (One trait)
Example: Crossing tall and dwarf pea plants
Parent Generation (P):
Tall (TT) √ó Dwarf (tt)
Gametes: T and t
F‚ÇÅ Generation:
All plants Tall (Tt)
‚Üí Only dominant trait appears (Tall).
Self-pollination of F‚ÇÅ:
F‚ÇÅ (Tt) √ó F‚ÇÅ (Tt)
F‚ÇÇ Generation (offspring):
Genotypic ratio: 1 TT : 2 Tt : 1 tt
Phenotypic ratio: 3 Tall : 1 Dwarf
üß© Conclusion: One trait (Tall) dominates over the other (Dwarf).

2Ô∏è‚É£ Dihybrid Cross (Two traits)
Example:
Round Yellow (RRYY) √ó Wrinkled Green (rryy)
F‚ÇÅ Generation:
All Round Yellow (RrYy)
Self-pollination of F‚ÇÅ:
(RrYy √ó RrYy)
F‚ÇÇ Generation:
Phenotypic ratio:
9 Round Yellow : 3 Round Green : 3 Wrinkled Yellow : 1 Wrinkled Green
üß© Conclusion: Traits are inherited independently (Law of Independent Assortment).

  ***Mandells three law of inheritance:
| Law                                  | Explanation                                                                                                            | Example                                    |
| ------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| **1. Law of Dominance**              | One factor (gene) dominates the other; the dominant trait appears in F‚ÇÅ.                                               | Tall (T) is dominant over Dwarf (t).       |
| **2. Law of Segregation**            | Each trait is controlled by two factors (alleles) which separate during gamete formation; only one enters each gamete. | TT ‚Üí gametes have T and T; tt ‚Üí t and t.   |
| **3. Law of Independent Assortment** | Genes for different traits are inherited independently of each other.                                                  | Seed color and shape behave independently. |

**Summury chart:
| Cross Type | Traits Studied | F‚ÇÅ Result           | F‚ÇÇ Ratio (Phenotypic) | Law Illustrated               |
| ---------- | -------------- | ------------------- | --------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Monohybrid | 1              | All dominant        | 3:1                   | Law of Dominance, Segregation |
| Dihybrid   | 2              | All dominant traits | 9:3:3:1               | Independent Assortment        |


üß¨ 1. Chromosomes
üìñ Definition:
Chromosomes are thread-like structures made of DNA and proteins (histones) present inside the nucleus of every cell.
They carry hereditary information from parents to offspring.

  | Feature              | Description                                                                   |
| -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Location**         | Inside the **nucleus** of cells                                               |
| **Made up of**       | DNA + Protein (histones)                                                      |
| **Function**         | Carry genetic information (genes)                                             |
| **Number in Humans** | **46 chromosomes (23 pairs)**                                                 |
| **Types**            | (1) **Autosomes** ‚Äì 22 pairs <br> (2) **Sex Chromosomes** ‚Äì 1 pair (XX or XY) |

**Human Chromosomes details:
| Type                | Description                                             | Example                |
| ------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------- |
| **Autosomes**       | Control normal body traits like height, eye color, etc. | 1‚Äì22 pairs             |
| **Sex Chromosomes** | Determine gender                                        | XX = Female, XY = Male |

üß´ 2. Genes
üìñ Definition:
A gene is a segment of DNA on a chromosome that controls a specific trait or character.
Each gene acts as a blueprint for making a particular protein that determines a characteristic (like eye color, blood type, etc.).

**Key points about gense:
| Feature                       | Description                                            |
| ----------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Location**                  | On chromosomes (at specific position called **locus**) |
| **Made of**                   | DNA                                                    |
| **Function**                  | Controls traits by making proteins                     |
| **Unit of inheritance**       | Gene                                                   |
| **Different forms of a gene** | **Alleles** (e.g., T/t for tall/dwarf)                 |

  üß© Example:
For plant height in pea plants:
T = gene for tallness (dominant)
t = gene for dwarfness (recessive)
Combination TT / Tt ‚Üí Tall, tt ‚Üí Dwarf

** diff in genes, chromosomes, DNA
| Level          | Description                         | Example               |
| -------------- | ----------------------------------- | --------------------- |
| **Cell**       | Basic unit of life                  | Skin cell, nerve cell |
| **Nucleus**    | Controls activities of cell         | Contains chromosomes  |
| **Chromosome** | Thread-like structure made of DNA   | Humans have 46        |
| **DNA**        | Long molecule carrying genetic code | Double helix          |
| **Gene**       | Segment of DNA controlling a trait  | Eye color gene        |

üìä In short:
üëâ Cell ‚Üí Nucleus ‚Üí Chromosome ‚Üí DNA ‚Üí Gene

üß¨ What is DNA?
Full form: Deoxyribonucleic Acid
Definition:
DNA is a long, double-stranded molecule that carries the genetic instructions used in the growth, development, functioning, and reproduction of all living organisms.
It is often called the ‚ÄúBlueprint of Life.‚Äù

**Location:
| Organism                        | Location of DNA                                               |
| ------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Eukaryotes (like humans)**    | Inside the **nucleus** (also small amount in mitochondria)    |
| **Prokaryotes (like bacteria)** | In the **cytoplasm** (nucleoid region) ‚Äî not inside a nucleus |

** Structure
üß© Structure of DNA
üß≠ Described by:
James Watson and Francis Crick in 1953
They proposed the Double Helix Model of DNA.
(Rosalind Franklin provided X-ray photographs that helped this discovery.)

Main structural feature:
| Feature                | Description                                                 |
| ---------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Shape**              | Double helix (like a twisted ladder)                        |
| **Strands**            | Two long chains running opposite each other (anti-parallel) |
| **Backbone**           | Made of **Sugar (Deoxyribose)** and **Phosphate** molecules |
| **Rungs (steps)**      | Made of **Nitrogen bases** paired together                  |
| **Bond between bases** | **Hydrogen bonds**                                          |
| **Total unit**         | Many nucleotides joined together                            |

üß± Components of a DNA Nucleotide
Each nucleotide (the building block of DNA) has 3 parts:
Deoxyribose sugar
Phosphate group
Nitrogen base

4 nitrogen bases:
| Base Type      | Name     | Symbol | Pairs With   |
| -------------- | -------- | ------ | ------------ |
| **Purine**     | Adenine  | A      | Thymine (T)  |
| **Purine**     | Guanine  | G      | Cytosine (C) |
| **Pyrimidine** | Thymine  | T      | Adenine (A)  |
| **Pyrimidine** | Cytosine | C      | Guanine (G)  |

Base pairing rule:
üß© A ‚Äî T (2 hydrogen bonds)
üß© G ‚Äî C (3 hydrogen bonds)

**Function Of DNA:
| Function                          | Explanation                                         |
| --------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| **1. Heredity**                   | DNA carries genes from parents to offspring.        |
| **2. Protein synthesis**          | DNA codes for proteins that control traits.         |
| **3. Control of cell activities** | DNA directs cell growth, repair, and metabolism.    |
| **4. Mutation**                   | Small changes in DNA cause variation and evolution. |

üß¨ DNA and Genes Relationship
Gene = A small section of DNA that carries instructions to make a specific protein.
Many genes together form a chromosome.
üëâ DNA ‚Üí Gene ‚Üí Protein ‚Üí Trait

üå± Variation ‚Äî Definition
Variation means the differences in characters or traits among the individuals of the same species.
‚û°Ô∏è In simple terms, no two individuals (except identical twins) look exactly the same ‚Äî these small or large differences are called variations.

üß¨ Cause of Variation
Variations arise mainly due to:
1)Genetic causes (inherited variation):
During sexual reproduction, genes are shuffled when gametes (sperm and egg) combine.
Crossing over during meiosis leads to new gene combinations.
Mutations (sudden changes in DNA) also cause variation.

2)Environmental causes (acquired variation):
Due to changes in environment, food, climate, or lifestyle.
Example: a person becomes strong by exercising ‚Äî not inherited to the next generation.

**Types of variation:
| Type                         | Description                                    | Example                                  |
| ---------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| **Inherited (Genetic)**      | Passed from parents to offspring through genes | Eye color, hair type, blood group        |
| **Acquired (Environmental)** | Develops during lifetime, not passed on        | Learning to play guitar, tanning of skin |
| **Continuous**               | Small differences that blend gradually         | Height, weight                           |
| **Discontinuous**            | Clear-cut differences                          | Blood group (A, B, AB, O)                |

Eg:
üß† Examples
In a population of bacteria, few may survive when antibiotics are added ‚Äî due to variation, those with resistance survive and reproduce.
Some plants tolerate drought better ‚Äî variation helps them live in dry regions.
